Gentlemen Prefer Blondes (1953)

Anita Loos old story from the 1920s about a pair of single women in search of husbands gets a makeover in Howard Hawks 1953 musical, starring Jane Russell and Marilyn Monroe as friends who go to Paris looking for mates. The film is charged by Hawks stylish snap, a famous set piece or two (Monroe descending that staircase while singing Diamonds Are a Girls Best Friend), Russells wit, and songs by Leo Robin and Jule Styne. The film may largely be a fluff project best remembered as a showcase for its leading actresses, but then Monroe and Russell rarely got such extended opportunities to prove that they were more than cinematic icons.
